Violent clashes erupted between Zimbabwean and Lesotho nationals in the Western Cape over employment on farms. It has been alleged that Zimbabweans are taking jobs from Lesotho nationals on local farms. National organising secretary of Commercial Stevedoring Agricultural and Allied Workers Union, Karel Swart speaks to #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Labour brokers are the root of the problem at the Cape Winelands in Robertson. That's according to the national organising secretary of Commercial, Stevedoring, Agricultural and Allied Workers Union's Karel Swart. This comes after clashes erupted between Zimbabwean and Lesotho nationals over jobs on farms. READ: The jobs emergency | Nxesi says all workers have rights Swart says the situation has calmed down since Friday when public order police intervened. He said "the problem is labour brokers, that is the heart of the problem. "Unless we address this decisively and finding a permanent solution we will sit with this problem forever. People allege that there are Lesotho labour brokers who only employ Lesotho nationals then tensions build up between our local people in the area and on the other hand you see Zimbabwean people." "The tension was between Lesotho workers and Zimbabwean migrants. People allegedly say these brokers only provide jobs to Lesotho’s. People then decide that if there is no fairness or equality, then nobody must go to work."